  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">International</h3>

  <p>According to the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the global economy is beginning to record a generalized and more aggressive slowdown than expected, while at the same time recording the highest inflation levels in decades. </p>

  <p>Despite the above, inflation is expected to decline gradually to 6.5% by 2023 and to 4.1% during 2024; to this end, the IMF expects that monetary and fiscal policy will continue to focus, through interest rate hikes, on alleviating the pressure on the cost of living and, finally, to give way to structural reforms that respond to the post-pandemic economic readjustment. </p>

  <p>The Eurozone maintains a conservative outlook due to the ongoing conflict in Eastern Europe and the resulting energy crisis. To face this, the European Union has increased purchases of natural gas from Norway and Algeria, thus avoiding recourse to Russia. </p>

  <p>The slowdown is expected to begin in the United States from the fourth quarter of 2022 and continue through the first half of next year, before resuming a growth path from the second half of 2023.  </p>

