  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">National</h3>

  <p>Mexico faces a challenging environment as global inflation rises, however, cautious macroeconomic management has allowed the country to maintain a position that allows it to move forward with stability, even in a context of economic instability.</p>

  <p>Jose Angel Gurria, former Secretary General of the OECD, commented that Mexico is able to attract investments to exceed 2% annual economic growth in the medium term. Likewise, the rating agency S&P stated that Mexico has fiscal strengths that allow it to maintain its sovereign rating two levels above Investment Grade, at "BBB/stable outlook", even in the midst of the complex global economic outlook and despite the risk of recession in the United States.  </p>

  <p>The International Monetary Fund (IMF) maintains an economic growth forecast for 2022 of 2.4%, while the Economic Commission for Latin America (ECLA) adjusted its forecast to 1.9%. Meanwhile, members of the banking sector, such as BBVA Mexico, maintain an estimate of 2.0%. </p>


  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">Industry</h3>

