  <p>Although the construction industry has shown improvements in the value of production during 2022, Mexico's economic situation continues to present complications.  </p>

  <p>According to a study by Bimsa Reports, construction companies in Mexico remain optimistic about the future; however, concerns about the economic environment persist. Specifically, they consider that 2022 has been a slightly better year than 2021 in terms of the volume of contracted work, although the main beneficiaries have been the larger construction companies. </p>

  <p>In terms of risks, the main concerns are the increase in the cost of construction materials (about 13% YoY), the lack of investment and the cost of financing. </p>

  <p>In the housing sector, during the quarter, INFONAVIT announced measures to increase the number and quality of credit granted, expanding the age limit to apply for a loan, going from 65 to 70 years old.  As a result, the maximum loan amount will increase by an average of MXN 180,000, and monthly payments will be lower. This contributed to an additional potential demand of approximately 200,000 eligible borrowers who meet the new requirements. </p>

  <p>In addition, INFONAVIT's potential demand in the markets where CADU operates shows signs of recovery, since in Quintana Roo alone, its main operating market, potential demand has increased by more than 23% so far in 2022 (data as of June) vs. December 2021. </p>

  <p>In the near future, FOVISSSTE will attend to credit requests on a continuous basis, eliminating application periods and thus making it easier to obtain mortgage loans for home purchases. </p>

